<!-- Research Work 1 -->

<div style="margin-right: 2em;font-size: 1em;margin-bottom:1em;width:100%">
      <h2><a href="https://www.cogcomneurosci.com/">Verguts Lab</a> (Ghent University)</h2>
      
     <div class = "research-logo">
          <img src="/images/gent-university.png" class="logo">
      </div>

      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-right: 1em;margin-bottom:-1em;">
      	 <p><b>Location:</b><br/>Ghent, Belgium</p>
      </div>
      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-bottom:-1em;">
      	 <p><b>Year:</b><br/>2018 - 2019</p>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
      
      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-right: 1em;margin-bottom:-1em;">
          <p><b>Subject:</b><br/>Computational Synchrony<br/>Model of Cognitive Control</p>
      </div>
      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-bottom:-1em;">
      	<p><b>Role:</b><br/>Graduate Research<br/>Assistant</p>
      </div>
      <div class="clearfix"></div>
      
      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-right: 1em;margin-bottom:-1em;">
      	<p><b>Team:</b>
         <ul>
         	<li>Rien Sonck </li>
            <li><a href="https://users.ugent.be/~tverguts/Site/Home.html">Prof. Dr. Tom Verguts</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://sites.google.com/site/senoussim/">Dr. Mehdi</a></li>
         </ul>
          </p>
      </div>
      <div style="width: 40%; float:left;margin-bottom:-1em;">
      	<p><b>Code and Documents:</b>
         	<ul>
         		<li><a href="https://github.com/riensonck/sync-model">GitHub</a></li>
         	</ul>
         </p>
      </div>
		<div class="clearfix"></div>
      <p style="text-align:justify;"><b>Description:</b><br/> Implementing flexibility mechanically has been a key computational issue in the cognitive control literature. 
      To achieve this, Verguts (2017) developed a model of cognitive control based on oscillatory mechanisms. This model employs “binding by random bursts”, 
      a combination of two principles, namely, communication-through-coherence and noise-induced synchronisation. 
      The aim of this project is to investigate the behavioural consequences of oscillatory mechanisms in the model.</p>
</div>
